\v 17 and that's why I sentÂŠ114528 TimothyÂŠ114530 to \add visit\add* you. He's like my own dear son in \nd YahwehÂŠ114540\nd*, and he'll remindÂŠ114543 you all about my waysÂŠ114545 in \nd MessiahÂŠ114549 Yeshua\nd*, just like I teachÂŠ114556 everywhere in every church.
\p
\v 18 \add Now\add* some of you have become arrogantÂŠ114564, as if I'm not able to come back to see you all,
\v 19 but if the \nd masterÂŠ114573\nd* allows it, I'll come andÂŠ114575 visit youÂŠ114570 all again soon. Then I won'tÂŠ114577 just see what any puffed-up people are \em saying\em*, but I'll also see what \em powerÂŠ114584\em* they have,
\v 20 becauseÂŠ114586 God's kingdomÂŠ114590 isn'tÂŠ114585 just mere words, butÂŠ114593 it's \add a demonstration of\add* powerÂŠ114595.
\v 21 What would you all prefer: should I come to you all with a rod, or \add come\add* with love and a gentleÂŠ114609 spiritÂŠ114606?
\c 5
\s1 Expelling the sexually immoral
\rem /s1 Expel the Immoral Brother!; Paul Condemns Spiritual Pride; Sexual Immorality Defiles the Church; Immorality in the Church
\p
\v 1 ActuallyÂŠ114610, we've been hearing that there's sexual immorality there among youÂŠ114614 all, andÂŠ114616 so bad that even non-believers don'tÂŠ114620 do it: a man is sleeping with his step-mother!\x + \xo 5:1: \xt Deu 22:30.\x*
\v 2 ThenÂŠ114632 instead of being upset, you all \add seem\add* proud of it. This man should have been expelled out of yourÂŠ114645 \add group\add*,
\v 3 because even though I'm not there physically, I am present in the spiritÂŠ114662, and I've alreadyÂŠ114663 made my judgementÂŠ114664 about the man who's doing this, as if I were present.
\v 4 When you assemble togetherÂŠ114679 in the name of ourÂŠ114676 master Yeshua, my spiritÂŠ114684 \add is there\add* along with the master \nd Yeshua's\nd* powerÂŠ114687,
\v 5 \add then you should\add* hand this man over to SatanÂŠ114698 to \add punish\add* his bodyÂŠ114702, so that his spiritÂŠ114705 can be savedÂŠ114706 for when the \nd masterÂŠ114711\nd* \add returns\add*.
\p
\v 6 It isn't goodÂŠ114716 how you all boastÂŠ114718. Don't you realise that a littleÂŠ114723 bit of yeast can raise a whole loaf \add of bread\add*?\x + \xo 5:6: \xt Gal 5:9.\x*
\v 7 Get rid of the old yeast so that you'll all become fresh dough, just as you are unleavenedÂŠ114740 bread. BecauseÂŠ114742 \nd MessiahÂŠ114749\nd*, ourÂŠ114745 Passover lamb, has also been sacrificedÂŠ114748\x + \xo 5:7: \xt Exo 12:5.\x*
\v 8 so that weÂŠ114751 can be feastingÂŠ114751, not with old yeast or with yeast of evil and wickednessÂŠ114763, butÂŠ114762 with unleavenedÂŠ114766 breadÂŠ114766 of sincerityÂŠ114767 and of truthÂŠ114769.\x + \xo 5:8: \xt Exo 13:7; Deu 16:3.\x*
\rem /s1 Sexual Immorality Must Be Judged
\p
\v 9 I wroteÂŠ114770 to youÂŠ114771 in my letterÂŠ114774 not to associateÂŠ114776 with sexuallyÂŠ114777 immoralÂŠ114777 people,
\v 10 \add butÂŠ114790\add* certainlyÂŠ114780 not \add meaning\add* worldly people who are sexuallyÂŠ114782 immoralÂŠ114782 or swindlersÂŠ114792 or idolatersÂŠ114794, becauseÂŠ114795 \add that would mean that\add* you'd all have to leave this world.
\v 11 \add No,\add* I'm writing to tell youÂŠ114807 all not to associateÂŠ114809 with any so-called believer who's sexuallyÂŠ114815 immoralÂŠ114815 or greedy or an idolaterÂŠ114820 or verbally abusive or a drunkardÂŠ114825 or a swindlerÂŠ114827. Don'tÂŠ114808 even have a meal with such a person.
\p
\v 12 Why would it be my \add job\add* to judge outsidersÂŠ114838â\add no,\add* shouldn't it be those \em insideÂŠ114843\em* \add the assemblies\add* that you judge?
\v 13 \nd GodÂŠ114854\nd* will judge the outsidersÂŠ114852, \add butÂŠ114850\add*:\x + \xo 5:13: \xt Deu 13:5; 17:7 (LXX).\x* âExpelÂŠ114858 evilÂŠ114862 \add people\add* from among yourselvesÂŠ114865.â
\c 6
\s1 Lawsuits among believers
\rem /s1 Lawsuits against Fellow Christians; Lawsuits among Christians; Avoiding Lawsuits with Christians
\p
\v 1 If anyoneÂŠ114867 among youÂŠ114869 all has a case againstÂŠ114872 anotherÂŠ114874 \add believer\add*, how dare they go to \add a secular\add* court in front of an unbelieving judgeÂŠ114875 instead of to believers.
\v 2 Don'tÂŠ114885 you realise that \add in the future\add*, believers will judge the world, andÂŠ114893 if the world's going to be judgedÂŠ114897 by all of you, surely you're competent enough \add now\add* to judge smaller cases?
\v 3 Don'tÂŠ114909 youÂŠ114905 realise that we'll judge \add God's\add* messengersÂŠ114907? So surely we can judge things of \add this\add* life?
\v 4 \add So then,\add* if you have legal disputes about things of this life, why do you appoint people with no standing in the assemblyÂŠ114922 as judges?
\v 5 I say \add that\add* to your shameÂŠ114926. Don'tÂŠ114931 you have anyoneÂŠ114936 among you all who can arbitrate between believers?
\v 6 ButÂŠ114954 instead, one believer goes to court against another, andÂŠ114954 it's in front of unbelieversÂŠ114958!
\p
\v 7 Actually, you're all disgraced already for havingÂŠ114970 lawsuitsÂŠ114968 among yourselvesÂŠ114972. Why not rather be wrongedÂŠ114977? Why not rather be cheated?
\v 8 ButÂŠ114988 you're all wrongingÂŠ114987 and cheating \add others, includingÂŠ114988\add* fellowÂŠ114993 believersÂŠ114993.
\rem /s1 Avoiding Sexual Sin
\p
\v 9 Or don'tÂŠ114995 youÂŠ114996 all know that \add âthose who disobey\add* \nd GodÂŠ115001\nd* won'tÂŠ114995 inheritÂŠ115004 his kingdomÂŠ115002? Don'tÂŠ114995 let yourselves be deceivedÂŠ115006: those who are sexuallyÂŠ115008 immoralÂŠ115008 or idolatersÂŠ115010, or adulterersÂŠ115012 or male prostitutes or homosexuals,
\v 10 or thievesÂŠ115019 or greedy, or drunkardsÂŠ115028 or slanderers or swindlersÂŠ115032, will inheritÂŠ115036 God's kingdomÂŠ115033.
\v 11 Now some of you all were like that, butÂŠ115037 now you've been washedÂŠ115042 and declared guiltless, and been declared innocent by the authority of the \nd masterÂŠ115051 Yeshua MessiahÂŠ115054\nd*, and by ourÂŠ115061 god's \nd spiritÂŠ115058\nd*.
\s1 Avoid sexual immorality
\rem /s1 Glorify God in Body and Spirit; Use Your Bodies for God's Glory
\p
\v 12 Some might say, âEverything is permissible for me,â but not everything is beneficialÂŠ115068. Everything might be permissible for me, but I don'tÂŠ115066 want those things to have control over me.\x + \xo 6:12: \xt 1Cor 10:23.\x*
\v 13 You might say, âFood is for the stomach, and the stomach for food,â but \nd GodÂŠ115089\nd* will \add eventually\add* abolish them both. AlsoÂŠ115096, the body is not \add meant to be used\add* for sexualÂŠ115100 immoralityÂŠ115100, but rather, for the master, and the master for the body.
\v 14 \add Actually,\add* \nd GodÂŠ115111\nd* made the \nd masterÂŠ115114\nd* come alive again, andÂŠ115116 by hisÂŠ115124 powerÂŠ115123, he'll also do that for us.
\p
\v 15 Surely you all know that your bodiesÂŠ115129 are parts of messiah's \add body\add*? Because of that, you shouldn't take your body back and then join it to a prostitute'sÂŠ115143 \add body\add*. May it never happen!
\v 16 Or don'tÂŠ115148 youÂŠ115149 know that having sex with a prostituteÂŠ115154 is a joining togetherÂŠ115152, becauseÂŠ115159 it says:\x + \xo 6:16: \xt Gen 2:24.\x* âThe twoÂŠ115162 will become one bodyÂŠ115156.â
\v 17 But a person joining with the \nd masterÂŠ115170\nd*, becomes one spiritÂŠ115172 \add with him\add*.
\p
\v 18 \add Don't just walk away\add* from sexual immorality, but \em run away\em* from it, because other forms of disobeying God are outsideÂŠ115183 the body, but sexual immorality is a sin againstÂŠ115190 your own body.
\v 19 Surely you all know that yourÂŠ115203 bodyÂŠ115201 is a templeÂŠ115204 of the holy \nd spiritÂŠ115209\nd* who comes from \nd GodÂŠ115215\nd* andÂŠ115216 \add lives\add* within you.\x + \xo 6:19: \xt 1Cor 3:16; 2Cor 6:16.\x* No, you don'tÂŠ115196 \add actually\add* own yourselvesÂŠ115220
\v 20 becauseÂŠ115222 a priceÂŠ115223 was paid to buy you, so honourÂŠ115224 \nd GodÂŠ115227\nd* with yourÂŠ115231 bodies.
\c 7
\s1 Advice concerning marriage
\rem /s1 Directions concerning Marriage; Instruction on Marriage; Sex, marriage, and divorce; Questions about Marriage
\p
\v 1 Now concerningÂŠ115241 what you all wroteÂŠ115244 \add to me\add*: âIt's good for a man not to touchÂŠ115250 a womanÂŠ115248.â
\v 2 However, becauseÂŠ115251 there is so much sexualÂŠ115254 immoralityÂŠ115254, each man shouldÂŠ115259 have his own wife, and each womanÂŠ115261 her own husbandÂŠ115264.
\v 3 Both husbands and wives have a marital duty to each other \add in terms of sexual needsÂŠ115274\add*:
\v 4 wives' bodies belong to their husbands, not to themselves, and similarly, husbands' bodies belong to their wives, not to themselves.
\v 5 Don'tÂŠ115309 deprive each other, except by mutual agreement so that you may devote yourselves to prayerÂŠ115321 for an agreed timeÂŠ115314, and then be together againÂŠ115323, so that SatanÂŠ115335 can'tÂŠ115309 \add easily\add* temptÂŠ115332 you all becauseÂŠ115336 of yourÂŠ115339 lack of self-control.
\p
\v 6 But that isn'tÂŠ115345 a commandÂŠ115347âI'm only suggesting that it's good to do,\f + \fr 7:6 \ft It's not clear here whether Paul is referring back to marriage here (v2), or to abstaining from sex to focus on praying (v5).\f*
\v 7 and I wish everyoneÂŠ115352 could be like me. ButÂŠ115349 each person has their own gift from \nd GodÂŠ115364\nd*âone has such-and-such a gift while someone else has a different one.
\p
\v 8 Now to the unmarriedÂŠ115376 andÂŠ115377 to the widowsÂŠ115379 I say that it's goodÂŠ115381 if theyÂŠ115387 remainÂŠ115387 like me,\f + \fr 7:8 \ft This is intentionally left ambiguous because we can't be certain what Paul meant here.\f*
\v 9 butÂŠ115393 if they don'tÂŠ115394 have self-control, they shouldÂŠ115396 marry becauseÂŠ115398 it's betterÂŠ115397 to marry than to burn \add with sexual desire\add*.
\p
\v 10 Now I (\add well,\add* not I, butÂŠ115410 the \nd masterÂŠ115412\nd*) commandÂŠ115407 marriedÂŠ115406 people that a wifeÂŠ115413 is not to be separatedÂŠ115417 from her husbandÂŠ115415\x + \xo 7:10-11: \xt Mat 5:32; 19:9; Mrk 10:11-12; Luk 16:18.\x*
\v 11 (butÂŠ115421 even if she might be separatedÂŠ115423, let her remainÂŠ115424 unmarriedÂŠ115425, or let her be reconciledÂŠ115429 to the husband), and a husband is not to divorce a wife.
\p
\v 12 ButÂŠ115450 to the rest I say (I, not the \nd masterÂŠ115443\nd*) that if any believing husband has an unbelievingÂŠ115449 wifeÂŠ115447 and she agrees to live with him, he shouldn'tÂŠ115441 divorce her.
\v 13 Similarly, if any womanÂŠ115461 has an unbelievingÂŠ115467 husband andÂŠ115460 he agrees to live with her, she shouldn'tÂŠ115476 divorce him.
\v 14 You see, the unbelieving husband is \add exposed to faith\add* through his wife, and the unbelieving wife is \add exposed to faith\add* through the believing husband, otherwiseÂŠ115500 yourÂŠ115504 childrenÂŠ115503 would be âdefiledâ, butÂŠ115490 now they are declared innocent.
\v 15 But if the unbelieverÂŠ115514 departs, let \add that person\add* go. In such cases, the believing spouse is not tied down \add to serving their departed spouse\add*, butÂŠ115528 \add rather\add* \nd GodÂŠ115534\nd* has calledÂŠ115530 us to peaceÂŠ115529.
\v 16 You see, how do you know, woman, whether you will \add cause\add* your husband to be saved? Or how do you know, man, whether you will \add cause\add* your wife to be saved?
\s1 Sticking to your social position
\rem /s1 The Life That the Lord Has Assigned; Live As God Called You
\p
\v 17 Nevertheless, each person shouldÂŠ115570 live according to how the \nd masterÂŠ115561\nd* has assigned them andÂŠ115571 how \nd GodÂŠ115567\nd* has calledÂŠ115565 them. That's what I teach in all the assembliesÂŠ115576.
\v 18 Anyone who was called and who was \add previously\add* circumcised, shouldn't become âuncircumcisedâ. Anyone who was called who was uncircumcised, shouldn't get circumcised.
\v 19 Circumcision is nothing andÂŠ115596 uncircumcisionÂŠ115598 is nothing, butÂŠ115601 obeying God's commandsÂŠ115603 \add is what counts\add*.
\v 20 Each person shouldÂŠ115615 maintain the position they were in when they were calledÂŠ115611:
\v 21 Were you a slave when you were calledÂŠ115617? Don't be concerned about that (but indeed, if you'reÂŠ115624 able to becomeÂŠ115626 free, then take the opportunity)
\v 22 becauseÂŠ115630 anyone who was a slave when they were called by \nd Yahweh\nd* is free in \nd Yahweh's\nd* \add sight\add*. Conversely, anyone who was free when they were called is the \nd messiah'sÂŠ115645\nd* slave.
\v 23 You all were boughtÂŠ115648 \add by God\add* for a priceÂŠ115647, \add so\add* don'tÂŠ115649 becomeÂŠ115650 slavesÂŠ115652 of peopleÂŠ115653.
\v 24 \add Again\add*\x + \xo 7:24 \xt 7:20\x* brothersÂŠ115658 andÂŠ115658 sistersÂŠ115658, each person shouldÂŠ115661 remainÂŠ115661 in the position they were in when they were calledÂŠ115657, \add but now serving\add* \nd GodÂŠ115664\nd*.
\s1 Suggestions about the unmarried and about widows
\rem /s1 Questions about the Unmarried and the Widows; The Unmarried and the Widows
\p
\v 25 Now concerningÂŠ115665 unmarried women, I don'tÂŠ115671 have instructions from \nd Yahweh\nd* butÂŠ115674 I'll give my opinionsÂŠ115673 as someone who's trustworthyÂŠ115680 thanks to \nd Yahweh's\nd* mercyÂŠ115677.
\p
\v 26 ThereforeÂŠ115683, I thinkÂŠ115682 it's good becauseÂŠ115687 of the distress that's about to come, that people should stay as they are \add currently\add*.
\v 27 If you're married, then don't try to get out of it. If you're not committed, don't look for a spouse.
\v 28 ButÂŠ115715 if a single guy or single girl get married, that's not a sin, butÂŠ115709 they'll \add likely\add* face difficult circumstances andÂŠ115715 I'm trying to spare you from that.
\p
\v 29 But brothersÂŠ115736 andÂŠ115736 sistersÂŠ115736, I will say this: the time is shortÂŠ115739, so from now on, even those who are married should live as if they're not.
\v 30 Those who are mourning should \add act\add* as if they're not, those who are celebrating should \add act\add* as if they're not, and those who are buyingÂŠ115767 \add act\add* as if they don'tÂŠ115757 own \add anything\add*,
\v 31 andÂŠ115771 those who are using this world, as if they're not using itÂŠ115781, becauseÂŠ115783 the present form of this world will soon pass away.
\p
\v 32 But I'd like you to be free from concern. Single men are concerned about things of the \nd master\nd*âpleasingÂŠ115801 the \nd master\nd*â
\v 33 butÂŠ115806 marriedÂŠ115807 men are concerned about worldlyÂŠ115811 affairsâwanting to pleaseÂŠ115813 their wivesâso they're dividedÂŠ115818. And unmarriedÂŠ115823 or single women
\v 34 are concerning about things of the \nd masterÂŠ115832\nd*âso that both their bodies and their spiritsÂŠ115841 can be separate \add from the world\add*âbutÂŠ115839 marriedÂŠ115844 women are concerned about worldly affairsâwanting to pleaseÂŠ115850 their husbandsÂŠ115853.
\p
\v 35 Now I saidÂŠ115862 \add all\add* that for yourÂŠ115858 benefitÂŠ115860ânot to load you all with rules, butÂŠ115855 to \add act\add* in ways that are appropriate andÂŠ115855 devotedÂŠ115873 to the \nd masterÂŠ115876\nd* without any distractions.
\p
\v 36 However, if a man thinksÂŠ115888 he's made the wrong decisions about his unmarried woman,\f + \fr 7:36-38 \ft Yes, âhis unmarried womanâ sounds strange, but it's not certain here (and in the next two verses) if Paul is writing about a father and \+em his unmarried daughter who's engaged\+em*, or about an engaged man deciding about \+em his fiancĂ©e\+em*.\f* if she's reached the age of marriage and it should proceed, then he should do what he plannedâhe's not sinningÂŠ115902âthey should get married.
\v 37 ButÂŠ115917 if the man has made up his mindÂŠ115910 and isn'tÂŠ115913 forced, butÂŠ115905 makes his own decision, and he's firmly decided to keep his own woman unmarried, then that would also be a good decision.
\v 38 That way, anyone allowing his unmarried woman to marry does well, butÂŠ115952 anyone who doesn't, makes a betterÂŠ115958 decision.
\p
\v 39 A wife is committed to herÂŠ115970 husband as long as he lives, but if he passes away, she's free to marry whoever she wants to, as long as he's a believer.
\v 40 However, in my opinionÂŠ115997, she'd be happier if she didn't marry again, and I think it's God's \nd spiritÂŠ116002\nd* \add that wants me to say that\add*.
\c 8
\s1 Behaviour about food offered to idols
\rem /s1 Food Sacrificed to Idols; The Question about Food Offered to Idols
\p
\v 1 Now, concerning \add food\add* that's been sacrificedÂŠ116009 to idols: We knowÂŠ116013 that we all have âknowledgeââknowledge breeds conceit butÂŠ116007 loveÂŠ116021 gives inner strength.
\v 2 Anyone who thinks they know something \add usually\add* doesn't know \add what they don'tÂŠ116030\add* know,
\v 3 butÂŠ116039 anyoneÂŠ116040 who loves God is knownÂŠ116045 by God.
\p
\v 4 Now \add back to\add* eating \add food\add* that's been offered to idols, weÂŠ116054 know that there'sÂŠ116051 only one \nd GodÂŠ116063\nd* andÂŠ116060 so worldlyÂŠ116059 idols are \add really\add* nothingÂŠ116056 \add at all\add*.
\v 5 Even though there are many so-called âgodsâ and âmastersÂŠ116087â \add said to\add* live in the heavensÂŠ116076 or earthÂŠ116080,
\v 6 we know there's \add only\add* one \nd GodÂŠ116092\nd*, who is the Father who created everything and we exist \add to honour him\add*. And we only have one \nd masterÂŠ116106\nd*, \nd Yeshua MessiahÂŠ116108\nd* who created everything and \add is also the source of our existence\add*.
\p
\v 7 ButÂŠ116139 not everyone knows this. Some people have been so used to \add trusting\add* idols that \add even now as believers\add* when they eat food that's been sacrificedÂŠ116136 to idols, \add they still think it's wrong\add* andÂŠ116139 so theirÂŠ116142 weak consciencesÂŠ116141 become defiledÂŠ116146.
\v 8 But food doesn't bring us closer to \nd GodÂŠ116155\nd*âwhat we eat makes us no better or worse off \add spiritually\add*.
\p
\v 9 However, be careful in case yourÂŠ116176 freedom becomesÂŠ116179 a reason that weaker \add believers might get confused\add* and stumbleÂŠ116178 in their \add spiritual walk\add*.
\v 10 \add Yes,\add* if someoneÂŠ116185 with a weaker conscience sees you eatingÂŠ116207 at a place with an idol, they might be encouraged to eat food that's offered to idols \add against their conscience\add*,
\v 11 thus this weaker believer who the \nd messiahÂŠ116225\nd* also diedÂŠ116226 for, \add might end up\add* beingÂŠ116209 destroyedÂŠ116209.
\v 12 If you end up sinning against other believersÂŠ116232 andÂŠ116228 woundingÂŠ116234 theirÂŠ116235 weak consciencesÂŠ116237, you sin against \nd MessiahÂŠ116240\nd*.
\v 13 ThereforeÂŠ116242, if food might cause a fellow believer to stumble, I'll certainly never eatÂŠ116251 meat, so that I won'tÂŠ116250 cause them to stumble.
\c 9
\s1 The missionary's responsibilities
\rem /s1 Paul Gives Up His Rights; Rights and Duties of an Apostle; The Rights of an Apostle
\p
\v 1 Aren't I free? Aren't I a missionary? Haven't I seen \nd Yeshua\nd* ourÂŠ116276 master? Aren't you all \add the result of\add* myÂŠ116281 work for \nd YahwehÂŠ116275\nd*?
\v 2 If I'm not a missionary to othersÂŠ116287, at least I am to all of you, becauseÂŠ116296 you're the proof that I'm a missionary for \nd YahwehÂŠ116305\nd*.
\v 3 That's my defenceÂŠ116308 to those who are questioning my role.
\p
\v 4 Don'tÂŠ116315 weÂŠ116317 have a rightÂŠ116318 to eatÂŠ116319 andÂŠ116320 drinkÂŠ116321?
\v 5 Don'tÂŠ116323 weÂŠ116324 have a rightÂŠ116325 to take alongÂŠ116328 a believing wifeÂŠ116327 like the rest of the missionaries and the \nd master'sÂŠ116338\nd* brothersÂŠ116336 and PeterÂŠ116340?
\v 6 Or it is only BarnabasÂŠ116345 andÂŠ116344 I who have to work \add to support ourselves\add*?
\v 7 What soldierÂŠ116353 has to pay his own expenses? Who plantsÂŠ116358 a vineyardÂŠ116359 and isn't \add allowed\add* to eat itsÂŠ116366 fruitÂŠ116365? Or who shepherdsÂŠ116371 a flock and isn't \add allowed\add* to drink the milkÂŠ116376 \add they produceÂŠ116365\add*?
\p
\v 8 Am I \add just\add* sayingÂŠ116394 this from a humanÂŠ116383 perspective? Doesn't \add Mosheh's\add* law also teach that?
\v 9 He wroteÂŠ116400 in those laws: âDon't prevent the ox from eating when it's \add working to\add* threshÂŠ116405 the grain.â\x + \xo 9:9: \xt Deu 25:4; 1Tim 5:18.\x*
\v 10 Isn't he saying that on \em our\em* behalf? \add Yes,\add* it was writtenÂŠ116420 for our sake \add saying\add* that anyone who's ploughing \add a field \add* should expect \add to be paid\add*, and anyone who threshesÂŠ116432 \add the grain\add* should expect a share of the harvest.
\v 11 If we sowedÂŠ116448 spiritualÂŠ116447 things among you, is it too much to expect a materialÂŠ116454 âharvestâ from you?\x + \xo 9:11: \xt Rom 15:27.\x*
\v 12 If otherÂŠ116458 people have the right to this \add kind of\add* support, don'tÂŠ116464 we have a greater right?
\p But we never took advantage of that rightâinstead we enduredÂŠ116475 everything so that we wouldn't do anything to hinder the \nd messiah'sÂŠ116487\nd* goodÂŠ116484 messageÂŠ116484 \add from spreading\add*.
\v 13 Don't you know that the temple workers eat from the temple \add budget\add*, and those who work at the altar receive a portion of what's offered?\x + \xo 9:13: \xt Deu 18:1.\x*
\v 14 Similarly, the \nd masterÂŠ116511\nd* even instructed that anyone who preaches the good message should be able to make their livingÂŠ116520 off it.\x + \xo 9:14: \xt Mat 10:10; Luk 10:7.\x*
\p
\v 15 ButÂŠ116530 I haven't taken advantage of \add any\add* of those rights, andÂŠ116530 even now, I'm not writing this to ask for material support for myselfâI'd ratherÂŠ116540 dieÂŠ116541 than have someone deprive me of this reason for boastingÂŠ116546.
\v 16 And yet, when I preach the good message, it doesn't give me any \add good\add* reason to boastÂŠ116561 becauseÂŠ116563 I'm \add actually\add* \em obligated\em* to do itâI wouldn't end well if I didn'tÂŠ116557 preach the good message
\v 17 becauseÂŠ116576 if I do it willinglyÂŠ116577, I'll have a rewardÂŠ116580, butÂŠ116583 if it's done unwillinglyÂŠ116584, I'd be \add shirking\add* the responsibility entrustedÂŠ116586 to me.
\v 18 SoÂŠ116588, what's myÂŠ116590 rewardÂŠ116593? It's preachingÂŠ116595 the good message and \add the privilege of\add* doing it free of chargeÂŠ116596, so as not to take advantage of the right that the good message \add gives me\add*.
\p
\v 19 Although I have no obligation to any person, I made myselfÂŠ116620 a slave of everyone in orderÂŠ116622 to win over as many as possible.
\v 20 To the Jews, I behave like the Jew \add that I am\add* in order to win them. To those under the \add traditional\add* rules, I behave like one of them (although I myselfÂŠ116644 am not under those rules) in order to win them over.
\v 21 To those outside \add our religious\add* rules, I behave like them (although not so far as to disobey God's law, because I'm under Messiah's law) in orderÂŠ116665 to win them over.
\v 22 To the weak, I become weak to win them over. \add Yes,\add* I'veÂŠ116680 become all things to all people so\f + \fr 9:27 \ft TODO: Investigate why so many other translations translate ÏÎŹÎœÏÏÏ something like âby all meansâ here (whereas our OET-LV gloss is âcertainlyâ).\f* that I might be certainÂŠ116685 of saving some.
\p
\v 23 I do all that for the sake of the goodÂŠ116694 messageÂŠ116694, so that I'll share in its blessings.
\v 24 Surely you all know that all the participants in a race run, but only one \add of them\add* gets the prize? Run in such a way that you get \add the prize\add*.
\v 25 But everyoneÂŠ116718 who competes has to exercise self-control in every aspect. They do it in orderÂŠ116728 to win a wreath that'll \add quickly\add* wilt, butÂŠ116719 weÂŠ116732 work towards one that never deteriorates.
