\v 2 Now I commend you all because you always think of what I teach and do, and because you carefully believe and do what I taught you all,
\v 3 but I want you all to know that the messiah is the head of everyÂŠ117332 man, and the man is the head of \add his wife\add*, and \nd GodÂŠ117349\nd* is the head of the messiah.\f + \fr 11:3 \ft The translators expect that this talk of âthe headâ is referring to authority, but because our modern society has become more sensitive to these issues, we decided to keep it literal here, thus letting our readers decide for themselves what Paul probably meant. (Having done that, our readers can also consider for themselves whether this might have been a cultural necessity in and around Corinth, or whether it has widespread application to all cultures.)\f*
\v 4 Any manÂŠ117352 who prays or speaks out a prophecyÂŠ117355 with his head covered is dishonouring his head,
\v 5 butÂŠ117365 any womanÂŠ117366 who prays or prophesiesÂŠ117369 with her head \em uncoveredÂŠ117370\em* dishonours her head, becauseÂŠ117380 it's just as if her head had been shavedÂŠ117386.
